================================================================================
Acknowledgements & third-party components
================================================================================

keen-manager is an ORCHESTRATOR. It manages proven, independently distributed
components rather than re-bundling them. This keeps licensing clean and lets each
component be updated from its own upstream.

Design and integration were informed by these MIT-licensed projects. keen-manager
is an independent work and is not endorsed by their authors:

  - hoaxisr/awg-manager            (MIT) — AmneziaWG management on Keenetic
    https://github.com/hoaxisr/awg-manager
  - nfqws/nfqws2-keenetic          (MIT) — nfqws2 packaging for Keenetic/Entware
    https://github.com/nfqws/nfqws2-keenetic
  - nfqws/nfqws-keenetic-web       (MIT) — web UI for nfqws
    https://github.com/nfqws/nfqws-keenetic-web

Components that keen-manager DRIVES but does NOT redistribute (installed from
their own upstreams by the installer, under their own terms):

  - nfqws2 daemon + Lua engine — from bol-van/zapret2. Upstream ships without an
    explicit license; keen-manager does not vendor or redistribute these binaries.
    It installs/updates the `nfqws2-keenetic` opkg package and drives it.
  - AmneziaWG kernel modules / userspace (amneziawg-go, amneziawg-tools) — the
    kernel modules derive from WireGuard/AmneziaWG and are effectively GPLv2.
    keen-manager does not bundle them; it uses packages present on the device.
  - Xray-core — from XTLS/Xray-core (MPL-2.0). Installed from upstream releases,
    not vendored here.

Bundled Go dependencies:
  - gopkg.in/yaml.v3 (MIT / Apache-2.0 dual portions) — see go.sum / module cache.
